<br>
As for your reply, most of it is horse manure, but I would point out that targeting a mob by using their feet or heads is a common tactic that most encs learn and use, but was never mentioned on your site.  It has nothing to do with outdoors or indoors, but lots of stacked mobs...ie..trains (something which occurs with a much lesser frequency outdoors).  When I was L30 asking L50's on our server how to target, it was one of the first things they would mention.  But no man, that’s not the only reason my comment was made and I really don’t feel like going through your site and picking out the statements which would lead me to believe that.  <br>
<br>
As for stam as a primary stat....well dude, you're in CT, maybe you just don’t play that much or maybe you don’t get shit for loot..I don’t know.  What I do know is that I have a 255 buffed Int and 220 Buffed Cha.  I have 3359 HP buffed and a 869 AC.  I know that I'd be more than willing to sacrifice 40 pts of int for an additional 80-100 HP.  If you don’t understand that...fight some AE mobs and maybe it will become much clearer to you.  If you are sure you will never be in a raid guild, then by all means put your points into Int, the gear you get outside of the &quot;uber&quot; rings (ie..NToV mobs and the like) will not nearly give you the amount of int that you require.  But if you have even the slightest inclination to be &quot;uber&quot; then put the points into stam...that is where they will be needed.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry you felt like my criticism of your site was a personal attack, I did not know you created it, (for that matter I don’t even know you), all's I knew is that while it was informative, I did not learn anything (I actually expected to) and it wasn't by any means excellent.  I did not say &quot;This site sucks, don’t read it&quot;  I simply said &quot;Learn it by doing&quot;.  <br>
<br>
Ironically...here's a quote FROM YOUR SITE:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If you were hoping you'd learn more from reading this section, I hope you can look back and see that I've told you everything you can be told.  I'm just hear to teach you how to learn what it means to control a crowd.  To actually deal with the pumping heart and anxiety of crunching impacts to your body, you have to be there--you have to do it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Gee....looks like we agree on something after all.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Two final notes...Claritii's post hit the nail on the head...We do not control crowds, we do not control mobs, we control time.  Our single purpose in the game is to make that which is already completely tedious and anally slow...faster.  We have the buffs that increase the uptime and decrease the down time. (C2, Haste, GoB, blah..) We have the abilities to reduce the amount of mana casters have to use and increase the amount of damage that melee do (Slow, Cripple, Mez, blah)...We became critical to a group simply for one fact...we make it all happen with ease and we look good doing it.  <br>
<br>
My second note...think for a moment...why is it that every single class has a definitive website or guide written for them but not the enchanter?  My theory...Too many people (especially now) are reading these site's and using the info there as though it were a bible.  They PL the class and never learn it.  That's fine for most classes...melee can get by just knowing how to assist and hit the attack key.  Wizards, necros and mages can get by knowing how to cast a nuke (I've only met one necro/mage, that I consider to be a great pet controller...He knows who he is boom boom.)  Shamans and druids can get by just by casting buffs and spot healing...but encs (and even clerics to an extent)...if you don’t know what you're doing then someone's going to die more than likely the entire group.  It's not just a class, it's a fraternity.  Anyone can level an enc to 60, but can you play the class when it's critical...that's what matters.<br>
<br>
Don't be so sensitive to criticism dude...it's not a good thing.<br>
